The 4th-ID is a very broad term that encompasses many things, but it boils down to the fact that society - as a whole - is now going through a massive change in labor and economic norms.\\n\\nThe transition from the 3rd to the 4th Industrial Revolution happened during the 10's when software and data companies overtook oil companies both in size and profitability, dominating the Fortune 500 lists and attention of the business communities as a whole. The old guard fought back, using whatever they could - government bailouts, academic and institutional pressure, the media (in their demonization of the tech industry), NIMBYism, economic shutdowns, etc...basically whatever they could to try to freeze time into place. This apparatus continues to create more and more economic casualties to this day - in the form of homelessness, income inequality and lack of economic mobility, high personal debt, and the rising costs of living that continues to grow each day.\\n\\nBut these measures - though extremely costly - have only served to delay, rather than stop the march of time. Data is still worth more than oil now and given that the latter is finite and the former is infinite, there is no reason to think that the clock will ever turn back. The Infomation Age (a transition from the 3rd-ID's Energy Age) is here to stay.\\n\\nConcepts like Universal Basic Income (UBI) were originally designed for moments like these - a permanent safety net for governments and citizens alike against the volatility of market swings and labor conditions that are ever-changing and hard to predict. UBI gives every citizen a degree of breathing room during market downturns, job transitions/unemployment, high inflation, unexpected healthcare costs, and just plain old bad luck. It's really an idea that good for everyone - including governments and the rich, who will receive its benefits in the form of a more stable, governable society to live in.\\n\\nBut it's a little too late for it at this point, so the revolution will like happen as it typically has during previous \\\"corrections\\\" in the past. The downturn coming in 22-23' will probably be the biggest market correction that has happened in the history of mankind, but the patterns in which it unfolds will likely stay the same. There is nothing new under the sun, after all - what's about to happen has already happened many times before - the only thing different this time will be its size and scale.\\n\\n--\\n\\nMuch has - and will be - talked about the Fourth Industrial Revolution and our transition into the new economic territory in the upcoming months and years by many people out there. But here I'd like to focus on the \\\"Silver Linings\\\" - the reality is not all change to come will be bad. But the key is to stay adaptable and be open to change - because that is the only way the global economy will stabilize in a way that actually makes sense. For that to happen, it's necessary to pay attention to the positive and growing trends that are still happening now.\\n\\n- Many sectors in the economy (including tech, and blue collar work like plumbing/electrical/masonry) are actually experiencing labor shortages and have been in that state for a while. Culturally, however, these professions have been \\\"status-bombed\\\" (i.e. looked down upon) by the old guard who have attempted to discourage people from entering these fields in fear of having to raise their own wages in order to compete for labor and talent. \\n\\nThese sentiments were reinforced by academia, the government, and the media at the same time and can be very difficult to escape since its basically everywhere at this point. But as these institutions start to crumble, so will their hold on people's minds - and people may more easily consider paths towards a decent living without the fear of social ostracization going forward.\\n\\nEconomic revolutions happen when people let go of the past and find new types of work that are more rewarding and lucrative at the same time -- and these oppotunities are still there, if you look. If you're thinking of doing a career change, moving to a new place, or are just looking something new in your life, now is probably the best time to do it, really.\\n\\n- High inflation has many downsides for many, but there are a few upsides, even for the average person out there: 1) it puts pressure on employers to raise wages, longer-term, 2) it puts pressure on businesses to stay adaptable to market conditions and trends, and 3) it lessens the impact on personal debt since the money owed becomes smaller relative to money gained. These are issues that have been major problems in the economy and even talked about regularly in the media - but now that the government and insitutional powers are running out of options, there may finally be some room for the average person to benefit from the new economic conditions.\\n\\nThough looked down upon by a number of employers, \\\"Quiet Quitting\\\" is the economically logical thing for workers to do. If employers want better performance, they will have to pay people more or risk going out of business as the core of the business itself comes to a halt. The reason why we call it a \\\"correction\\\" is because this downturn will cause many of the bad and under-paying actors in the business sector to simply disappear.\\n\\n- Historically low interest rates (most of the 10's) have produced a culture of \\\"continuous fundraising\\\", where the focus of startups and businesses have become that of raising money, rather than of revenue. It's one thing for non-profits to use taxpayer money to balance the budgets, but another thing for private businesses to forego the idea of profitability completely and rely on 2nd, 3rd, 4th, or even more rounds of fundraising to keep themselves alive.\\n\\nThe VC ecosystem is already tanking and are in disarray - and most governments around the world are now too broke to give out any more bailouts or cheap loans, even if they wanted to. As many economists have predicted: the party times are over, and now the hangover ensues. (They more the treasury prints, the more inflation goes up. The so-called \\\"death spiral\\\".)\\n\\nThe truth is that people, as a whole, have been overpaying for overpriced, inferior products for a very long time (especially for essentials such as housing, healthcare, and education) due to artificial economies and monopolies that severely limit consumer choices. All of that is about to be lifted, and the result should be higher quality products for everyone, overall.\\n\\n--\\n\\nRight now we're in a difficult situation where we have the worst of both worlds - the benefits of the old are fading while the upsides of the new hasn't quite kicked in yet (and still hard to decipher which initiatives are actually new vs ones that are just grifting) so it will take some time before the process of creative-destruction makes itself complete. But all trends point in the direction that this is happening now, and it is where we are going as a world as a whole.\\n\\nThe future is now. Or more accurately - the future was a decade ago, and we're just finally starting to realize it - now. Linings for the Fourth Industrial Revolution\\n\\nI talked about this a few years ago when I was advocating for Universal Basic Income (was supporting Andrew Yang back in 2020), but I do think it's safe to say that the Fourth Industrial Revolution is now happening as we speak. The 4th-ID is a very broad term that encompasses many things, but it boils down to the fact that society - as a whole - is now going through a massive change in labor and economic norms.\\n\\nThe transition from the 3rd to the 4th Industrial Revolution happened during the 10's when software and data companies overtook oil companies both in size and profitability, dominating the Fortune 500 lists and attention of the business communities as a whole. The old guard fought back, using whatever they could - government bailouts, academic and institutional pressure, the media (in their demonization of the tech industry), NIMBYism, economic shutdowns, etc...basically whatever they could to try to freeze time into place. This apparatus continues to create more and more economic casualties to this day - in the form of homelessness, income inequality and lack of economic mobility, high personal debt, and the rising costs of living that continues to grow each day.\\n\\nBut these measures - though extremely costly - have only served to delay, rather than stop the march of time. Data is still worth more than oil now and given that the latter is finite and the former is infinite, there is no reason to think that the clock will ever turn back. The Infomation Age (a transition from the 3rd-ID's Energy Age) is here to stay.\\n\\nConcepts like Universal Basic Income (UBI) were originally designed for moments like these - a permanent safety net for governments and citizens alike against the volatility of market swings and labor conditions that are ever-changing and hard to predict. UBI gives every citizen a degree of breathing room during market downturns, job transitions/unemployment, high inflation, unexpected healthcare costs, and just plain old bad luck. It's really an idea that good for everyone - including governments and the rich, who will receive its benefits in the form of a more stable, governable society to live in.\\n\\nBut it's a little too late for it at this point, so the revolution will like happen as it typically has during previous \\\"corrections\\\" in the past. The downturn coming in 22-23' will probably be the biggest market correction that has happened in the history of mankind, but the patterns in which it unfolds will likely stay the same. There is nothing new under the sun, after all - what's about to happen has already happened many times before - the only thing different this time will be its size and scale.\\n\\n--\\n\\nMuch has - and will be - talked about the Fourth Industrial Revolution and our transition into the new economic territory in the upcoming months and years by many people out there. But here I'd like to focus on the \\\"Silver Linings\\\" - the reality is not all change to come will be bad. But the key is to stay adaptable and be open to change - because that is the only way the global economy will stabilize in a way that actually makes sense. For that to happen, it's necessary to pay attention to the positive and growing trends that are still happening now.\\n\\n- Many sectors in the economy (including tech, and blue collar work like plumbing/electrical/masonry) are actually experiencing labor shortages and have been in that state for a while. Culturally, however, these professions have been \\\"status-bombed\\\" (i.e. looked down upon) by the old guard who have attempted to discourage people from entering these fields in fear of having to raise their own wages in order to compete for labor and talent. \\n\\nThese sentiments were reinforced by academia, the government, and the media at the same time and can be very difficult to escape since its basically everywhere at this point. But as these institutions start to crumble, so will their hold on people's minds - and people may more easily consider paths towards a decent living without the fear of social ostracization going forward.\\n\\nEconomic revolutions happen when people let go of the past and find new types of work that are more rewarding and lucrative at the same time -- and these oppotunities are still there, if you look. If you're thinking of doing a career change, moving to a new place, or are just looking something new in your life, now is probably the best time to do it, really.\\n\\n- High inflation has many downsides for many, but there are a few upsides, even for the average person out there: 1) it puts pressure on employers to raise wages, longer-term, 2) it puts pressure on businesses to stay adaptable to market conditions and trends, and 3) it lessens the impact on personal debt since the money owed becomes smaller relative to money gained. These are issues that have been major problems in the economy and even talked about regularly in the media - but now that the government and insitutional powers are running out of options, there may finally be some room for the average person to benefit from the new economic conditions.\\n\\nThough looked down upon by a number of employers, \\\"Quiet Quitting\\\" is the economically logical thing for workers to do. If employers want better performance, they will have to pay people more or risk going out of business as the core of the business itself comes to a halt. The reason why we call it a \\\"correction\\\" is because this downturn will cause many of the bad and under-paying actors in the business sector to simply disappear.\\n\\n- Historically low interest rates (most of the 10's) have produced a culture of \\\"continuous fundraising\\\", where the focus of startups and businesses have become that of raising money, rather than of revenue. It's one thing for non-profits to use taxpayer money to balance the budgets, but another thing for private businesses to forego the idea of profitability completely and rely on 2nd, 3rd, 4th, or even more rounds of fundraising to keep themselves alive.\\n\\nThe VC ecosystem is already tanking and are in disarray - and most governments around the world are now too broke to give out any more bailouts or cheap loans, even if they wanted to. As many economists have predicted: the party times are over, and now the hangover ensues. (They more the treasury prints, the more inflation goes up. The so-called \\\"death spiral\\\".)\\n\\nThe truth is that people, as a whole, have been overpaying for overpriced, inferior products for a very long time (especially for essentials such as housing, healthcare, and education) due to artificial economies and monopolies that severely limit consumer choices. All of that is about to be lifted, and the result should be higher quality products for everyone, overall.\\n\\n--\\n\\nRight now we're in a difficult situation where we have the worst of both worlds - the benefits of the old are fading while the upsides of the new hasn't quite kicked in yet (and still hard to decipher which initiatives are actually new vs ones that are just grifting) so it will take some time before the process of creative-destruction makes itself complete. But all trends point in the direction that this is happening now, and it is where we are going as a world as a whole.\\n\\nThe future is now. Or more accurately - the future was a decade ago, and we're just finally starting to realize it - now.
